{"key":"post-12733304","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12733304</id>\n<content>As has been said before, one of the reasons for soaking grains first is to soften them up and allow them to hydrate and expand slowly.&amp;nbsp; If you've soaked for anywhere from 4 hours to 24 hours, you can bring them to a boil without bursting.&amp;nbsp; Boil for a few minutes and then dump them into a strainer to steam dry on the surface before loading jars.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;As you found out, dropping dry grains into boiling water bursts them open, spilling the starch out.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12733468</next>\n<prev>12733294</prev>\n<first>12733289</first>\n<last>12733745</last>\n<when>1276394760</when>\n<utime>06/13/10 05:06 AM</utime>\n</post>"}